在[[希臘語|希臘語]]中，“{{lang|el|paiderastia}}（{{lang|el|παιδεραστία}}）”是一個陰性抽象名詞，由“{{lang|el|paiderastês}}”變化而來。而“{{lang|el|paiderastês}}”則是由“{{lang|el|Pais}}”''（希臘語“孩子”的意思）''和“{{lang|el|Erastês}}”''（釋義見下文）''組合而成。<ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/pederasty Etymologies] {{Wayback|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/pederasty |date=20160308130049 }} in ''American Heritage Dictionary'', ''Random House Dictionary'', and ''Online Etymology Dictionary''</ref> 雖然“{{lang|el|Pais}}”這個詞彙代表“孩子”的時候並不區分其性別，但是根據{{link-en|亨利·利德爾|Henry Liddell}}和{{link-en|羅伯特·斯科特 (哲學家)|Robert Scott (philologist)|Robert Scott|羅伯特·斯科特}}所著的《[[希英詞典|希英詞典]]》的定義，“{{lang|el|paiderastia}}”作為名詞表示“男孩們的愛”，作為動詞則表示“成為男孩的愛人”。<ref>{{tsl|en|Henry Liddell|Henry George Liddell}} and {{tsl|en|Robert Scott (philologist)|Robert Scott}}, ''A Greek-English Lexicon'' (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1940 9th ed., with 1968 supplement in 1985 reprinting), p. 1286.</ref>

自從（{{link-en|肯尼斯·丹佛|Kenneth Dover}}）的經典著作《[[希臘同性戀|希臘同性戀]]》出版以來，“erastês”（愛者）和“erômenos”（被愛者）就成了古希臘少年愛（{{lang|el|paiderastia}}）性愛角色的標準稱呼。<ref>The pair of terms are used both within and outside the field of classical studies. For surveys and reference works within the study of ancient culture and history, see for instance ''The World of Athens: An Introduction to Classical Athenian Culture'', a publication of the Joint Association of Classical Teachers (Cambridge University Press, 1984, 2003), pp. 149–150 [http://books.google.com/books?id=VgDKeqi4or8C&pg=PA149&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=15#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false online] {{Wayback|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=VgDKeqi4or8C&pg=PA149&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=15#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false |date=20140627104629 }}; John Grimes Younger, ''Sex in the Ancient World from A to Z'' pp. 91–92 [http://books.google.com/books?id=IEqPs2Toy7YC&pg=PA92&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=13#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false online.] {{Wayback|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=IEqPs2Toy7YC&pg=PA92&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=13#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false |date=20141030235955 }} Outside classical studies, see for instance Michael Burger, ''The Shaping of Western Civilization: From Antiquity to the Enlightenment'' (University of Toronto Press, 2008), pp. 50–51 [http://books.google.com/books?id=MQUs2QnC2F4C&pg=PA50&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=18#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false online] {{Wayback|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=MQUs2QnC2F4C&pg=PA50&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=18#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false |date=20140627104657 }}; Richard C. Friedman and Jennifer I. Downey, ''Sexual Orientation and Psychoanalysis: Sexual Science and Clinical Practice'' (Columbia University Press, 2002), pp. 168–169 [http://books.google.com/books?id=mwtokhymV_4C&pg=PA168&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=8#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false online] {{Wayback|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=mwtokhymV_4C&pg=PA168&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=8#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false |date=20140627104041 }}; Michael R. Kauth, ''True Nature: A Theory of Sexual Attraction'' (Springer, 2000), p. 87 [http://books.google.com/books?id=PzDKr-qCdTAC&pg=PA87&dq=erastes-eromenos+intitle:sexual&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=3&cd=2#v=onepage&q=erastes-eromenos%20intitle%3Asexual&f=false online] {{Wayback|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=PzDKr-qCdTAC&pg=PA87&dq=erastes-eromenos+intitle:sexual&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=3&cd=2#v=onepage&q=erastes-eromenos%20intitle%3Asexual&f=false |date=20140627104719 }}; Roberto Haran, ''Lacan's Four Fundamental Concepts of Psychoanalysis'' (2004), p. 165ff. [http://books.google.com/books?id=SOl1hki9tSMC&pg=PA165&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=6#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false online.] {{Wayback|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=SOl1hki9tSMC&pg=PA165&dq=erastes+eromenos&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3&cd=6#v=onepage&q=erastes%20eromenos&f=false |date=20140627103531 }}</ref> 這兩個詞源於希臘語的動詞詞根“erô”和“erân”（均有“去愛”的含義），其含義可以參見[[厄洛斯|厄洛斯]]（Eros）。在丹佛嚴格的二分法中，“erastês（愛者）”被視為關係中年長的一方，他通常處於性愛的主動或主導地位；<ref>Kenneth Dover, ''Greek Homosexuality'' (Harvard University Press, 1978, 1989), p. 16.</ref> 而“erômenos（被愛者）”則是關係中年輕的一方，他通常處於性愛的被動或從屬地位。需要指出的是，“erômenos”與“paiderastês”不同，後者往往表示一種貶義的“男孩情人”的含義。<ref>Liddell and Scott, ''Greek-English Lexicon'', p. 1286.</ref> 另外，“erastês（愛者）”的年齡一般也就是二十出頭而已，<ref>William Armstrong Percy III, ''Pederasty and Pedagogy in Archaic Greece'' (University of Illinois Press, 1996), p. 1 [http://books.google.com/books?id=TCvoj1efp8UC&pg=PA1&dq=%22in+his+early+twenties+the+young+aristocratic+lover%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=3&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22in%20his%20early%20twenties%20the%20young%20aristocratic%20lover%22&f=false online.] {{Wayback|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=TCvoj1efp8UC&pg=PA1&dq=%22in+his+early+twenties+the+young+aristocratic+lover%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=3&cd=1#v=onepage&q=%22in%20his%20early%20twenties%20the%20young%20aristocratic%20lover%22&f=false |date=20140627103634 }}</ref> 因此“erastês（愛者）”和“erômenos（被愛者）”之間的年齡差距並不是很大。<ref>Martha Nussbaum, "Platonic Love and Colorado Law: The Relevance of Ancient Greek Norms to Modern Sexual Controversies," ''Sex and Social Justice'' (Oxford University Press, 1999), p. 309: "because the popular thought of our day tends to focus on the scare image of a 'dirty old man' hanging around outside the school waiting to molest young boys, it is important to mention, as well, that the ''erastês'' might not be very far in age from the ''erômenos''."</ref>

